3. ANATOMY OF A COMPREHENSION PASSAGE
Understanding the structure of any passage
Every well-written passage has a predictable internal structure. Knowing this structure lets you locate
information faster during the exam.
n Opening Sentence(s)
Introduces the topic. Often states the main idea. This is WHERE you find the 'central theme' or 'main
idea' answer.
n Supporting Sentences
Give evidence, examples, facts, reasons that develop the main idea. Most detail questions are
answered here.
n Transitional Sentences
Link one idea to the next. Words like 'however', 'therefore', 'moreover', 'in contrast' signal transitions.
n Concluding Sentence(s)
Summarises or gives the final thought. Important for 'author's purpose' or 'conclusion' questions.
n NOTE: Highlight/underline the first and last sentence of each paragraph first — this alone answers 60%
of comprehension questions.
