9. FULL PRACTICE PASSAGE WITH SOLVED QUESTIONS
Practice Passage 1
The relationship between education and economic development has been a subject of extensive
debate among scholars and policymakers alike. Traditionally, education was viewed primarily as a
vehicle for transmitting cultural values and preparing citizens for civic participation. However, with
the rise of industrial economies in the twentieth century, a more utilitarian view of education began to
dominate: schools and universities were increasingly expected to produce a skilled workforce
capable of driving economic growth.
Contemporary research has complicated this picture further. Studies indicate that the returns to
education — measured in terms of individual wages and national productivity — are highly uneven.
Countries that have invested heavily in higher education without simultaneously developing their
industrial and service sectors have seen their educated populations migrate abroad in search of
suitable employment. This phenomenon, widely known as 'brain drain', represents a significant loss
of human capital for developing nations.
At the same time, there is compelling evidence that quality basic education — particularly literacy
and numeracy — provides a stronger foundation for long-term development than an exclusive focus
on higher education. Policymakers must therefore strike a careful balance, ensuring that
investments in education at all levels are aligned with the broader economic and social needs of
their societies.
