10. COMMON MISTAKES & HOW TO AVOID THEM
The 8 Biggest Mistakes in Comprehension
n Mistake 1: Answering from memory/general knowledge
Example: The passage says X, but I know from real life that Y is true, so I'll choose Y.
n Fix: ALWAYS answer from the passage ONLY. Your outside knowledge is irrelevant.
n Mistake 2: Not reading the question carefully
Example: Choosing the wrong option because you missed the word 'NOT' or 'EXCEPT' in the question.
n Fix: Read every question word-by-word. Circle 'NOT', 'EXCEPT', 'MOST LIKELY' before answering.
n Mistake 3: Choosing 'too narrow' options for main idea
Example: A detail from Para 2 is chosen as the main idea because it sounds important.
n Fix: Main idea = covers ALL paragraphs. Details = covers ONE paragraph only.
n Mistake 4: Choosing 'extreme' options
Example: Options with 'always', 'never', 'only', 'all', 'none' are usually wrong in comprehension.
n Fix: The passage rarely makes absolute claims. Moderate language is usually correct.
n Mistake 5: Guessing vocabulary meaning without reading context
Example: The student knows one meaning of a word and chooses it without checking context.
n Fix: Always read the surrounding 2–3 sentences before answering vocabulary questions.
n Mistake 6: Treating inference as imagination
Example: Choosing an option that seems possible but is not logically supported by the passage.
n Fix: An inference must follow NECESSARILY from what is stated, not just be possible.
n Mistake 7: Spending too much time on one question
Example: Spending 4–5 minutes on a single comprehension question and running out of time.
n Fix: If stuck, mark your best guess and move on. Come back if time permits.
n Mistake 8: Not reading the full passage before answering
Example: Answering questions after reading only Para 1, missing context from later paragraphs.
n Fix: Always skim the entire passage first, then answer questions.
